The highly elongated Drosophila mechanosensory bristle--a new model for studying 
polarized microtubule function.

Bitan A(1), Guild G, Abdu U.

Author information:
(1)Department of Life Sciences and the National Institute for Biotechnology in 
the Negev, Ben-Gurion University, Beer-Sheva, Israel.

Microtubules (MTs) are polar polymers that can facilitate asymmetric 
distribution of cell components, a process important for polarized cell growth. 
The highly elongated and polarized Drosophila mechnosensory bristle cytoplasm is 
filled with short MTs that constitute a significant component of the shaft 
cytoplasm. Inhibition of MT assembly affects biased axial growth in the bristle 
and highlights the importance of MTs for this process. We demonstrate that the 
vast majority of bristle MTs are organized in a polarized manner, minus-ends 
out. We also show that genetic disruption of the MT polarity affects the polar 
distribution of cell components and leads to an alteration in the biased axial 
shape of the bristle shaft. Thus, we suggest that the asymmetric organization of 
the MT population within the bristle cell shaft is necessary for the proper 
axial elongation of this cellular extension. We would also like to emphasize the 
benefits of using the bristle cell as a model for studying MTs and MT-binding 
proteins because changes to this cytoskeletal component result in easily 
recognized at the phenotypes.

