257. Clin Geriatr Med. 2010 May;26(2):241-7. doi: 10.1016/j.cger.2010.02.004.

Prostate cancer in the older man: conflict between tumor biology and medical 
advancement.

Cummings JM(1).

Author information:
(1)Division of Urology, University of Missouri School of Medicine, One Hospital 
Drive, M562, Columbia, MO 65212, USA. cummingsjm@health.missouri.edu

As overall life expectancy grows, clinicians will be confronted more often with 
diseases that although devastating in the young individual, will not affect 
survival and possibly even quality of life for those in the older age groups. 
Prostate cancer is an example of this. The challenge for the physician caring 
for these patients is to distinguish who is at risk and how much risk so that 
decisions can be made regarding the propriety of prostate cancer detection and 
treatment of each individual. In this article, these issues are discussed in a 
way that helps the clinician guide older men to better decisions regarding 
prostate cancer detection and therapy.

